South Africa has averaged 137 new COVID-19 cases over the last week. An expert believes the lockdown is succeeding in flattening the infection curve but it's still early days. Michael Appel takes a look. #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - An expert believes the lockdown is succeeding in flattening the infection curve, but warns that it is still early days. So far, South Africa has averaged 137 new COVID-19 cases over the last week. Healthcare actuary Shivani Ranchod says the nationwide lockdown has had a positive effect towards flattening the curve. READ: WHO commends SA on COVID-19 response as death toll rises to 65 “If you look at the number of hospitalisations and number of deaths, all of those data points are coming in under what we would have expected to see in a non-lockdown situation,” said Ranchod. She says although our fatality rate has remained comparatively low there are other factors including a large immuno-compromised population. “We still don’t know whether the positive effects of us having a younger population because we know the mortality rate is strongly related to age. READ: COVID-19: Virus will be with us for a long time: WHO "So our overall population structure is much younger than say Italy for example, but there are offsetting factors in terms of our burden of disease.” South Africa's COVID-19 cases have increased to 3,465 and the death toll remains at 58. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.